ial Anxieties in Literary Texts of the Early Sixteenth Century -- tChapter 15. America and the Epistemological Crisis of Space: An Afterthought -- tPart III: Globalization and the Nationalistic Backlash in Germany -- tChapter 16. Theory of Early Modern Globalization -- tChapter 17. The Emerging Global Trade from a German Perspective -- tChapter 18. The Backlash Against the New Economy -- tChapter 19. Macro-Economic Critique of the Emerging Global Trade -- tChapter 20. Nationalistic and Xenophobic Responses to Foreign Influences -- tChapter 21. The Global Spice Trade: Breaching Traditional Values and Violating the Divine Order -- tChapter 22. The Backlash Against Globalization: The Rhetoric of Moral Decline and the Nostalgia Project -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA critical reading of both literary and non-literary German texts published between 1490 and 1540 exposes a populist backlash against perceived social and political disruptions, the dramatic expansion of spatial and epistemological horizons, and the growth of global trade networks. These texts opposed the twin phenomena of pluralization and secularization, which promoted a Humanist tolerance for ambiguity, boosted globalization and spatial expansion around 1500, and promoted new ways of imagining the world. Part I considers threats to the political order and the protestations against them, above all a vigorous defense of the common good. Part II traces the intellectual and epistemological upheaval triggered by the spatial discoveries and the new methods of visual and verbal representation of space. Part III examines the nationalistic backlash triggered by the rising global trade and related abusive trading practices and by perceived undue foreign influences. It is the basic premise of this book that the texts examined here protested the observed disruptions of the status quo and 